          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Overpowered Sword<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(2.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10576'>sean "lic0rice" smith</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10576&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 19, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Rayje&#39;s Sword, a 0e Universal Relic, has the following effect: Piercing - Spells, Powers, and Effects do not reduce energy loss.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, before I really get into it, there&#39;s something which everyone needs to understand. I&#39;m sure everyone realizes this already, but it still needs to be said. The entire game of MND is based on energy, and specifically upon controlling/producing/discarding more energy than the opponent. There are a rather large amount of ways to do this effectively, but each deck and region has specific ways to accomplish these goals. <br>
<br>
The easiest and most prominent way, of course, is not to make your opponent lose more energy, but to make you lose less energy. There are several entire regions (Kybar&#39;s Teeth, Underneath) who&#39;s main strategy relies on them losing less energy. Aside from that, there are even more cards, scattered between various regions, that produce the same effect (Olabra, Mydra, Agram&#39;s Armor, Tranquility) that are quite widely used. The most powerful creatures (Pylofuf, Braggle, Rock Hyren) all have some sort of energy loss prevention effect, which is what makes them usuable at all.<br>
<br>
Rayje&#39;s Sword cuts through all of the aformentioned techniques, laying low any strategy or hope for winning at all. This relic is far overpowered for the following reasons. A) It completely negates a HUGE amount of otherwise very playable cards, and in some cases, is the bane of entire regions. B) It is rather difficult to prevent it from being played, or to destroy it after it has been played before it has already cause too much damage.<br>
<br>
Rayje&#39;s Sword comepletely negates the following cards and effects, cards which are the bread and butter of otherwise tournament-worthy decks: Pylofuf, Strag&#39;s Ring, Gyrg, Parmalags, Braggle, Invulnerability, Shards of the Great Fossil, Mydra, and many others. The sheer number of strategies and otherwise competent decks that almost auto-lose to anything packing a Sword is just staggering.<br>
<br>
How easy is it to deal with a Sword once it has been played, before it ruins you? Not easy at all, because after playing the Sword, that player can continue playing all the damaging spells and attacks on their turn before you have a chance to act. Because there are very few cards in MND that can be played on other people&#39;s turns, the response time to the Sword is limited to after the Sword has fulfilled it&#39;s intended purpose. For instance, you could cast Bloom and Resonate the Sword. However, this not only requires 4e (assuming an Underneath Magi is casting), but the investment of two cards to remove one. Not only are you losing card advantage, but the Sword costs zero energy to put into play, putting the person who played it at an advantage already.<br>
<br>
The card advantage is also a huge factor, because the regions that would be more likely to use a Sword are also the regions that have massive card drawing engines, such as Bubble Xyx, Secrets of the Book, Aula, Cloud Scepter, Crushing Winds, Deep Barl, Corathan, Karak Necklace, Orothean Goggles, Barak the Red and more. The list just goes on and on. In the mean time, energy conservation decks have little to no card drawing mechanisms, which means that they will be harder pressed to find an answer to the Sword, and will have an even harder time with the second, and possibly the third Swords that are played. It&#39;s not uncommon for one of the draw decks to cycle through the entire deck two or three times before another deck has gone through once, thus allowing them to draw a Sword four or five times while the opposing deck has only drawn two forms or relic removal.<br>
<br>
When everyone is worried about Quido Swarms, Climbing Staffs, River Abaquists, and Rayje&#39;s Construct, look at the Sword. This is the card that needs to be errata&#39;d. It&#39;s mere prescence has kept otherwise good decks from being consistently feasible, and completely nullifies such a huge amount of game strategy and indivicual cards that it detracts more than it adds. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php?id=3987&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
